title: For Sale:  IBM - AO M1 Carbine .30 Caliber WWII USGI
postcontent: This is  a beautiful WW2 era M1 Carbine manufactured by the IBM Corporation. IBM-made M1 Carbines have long been sought after for a variety of reasons, one of them being the nostalgia that a company that ended up being known world-wide for making computers actually made carbines for the war effort. This M1 Carbine is what it is. I have no idea where it has been. It is simply an IBM U.S. M1 .30 Caliber carbine, stamped with an "AO" (built by subcontractor Auto Ordinance) marked receiver and original IBM Corp undated barrel.  Warning: Do not take this IBM technology into your local Apple Store for service. They just don't have a sense of humor!All kidding aside; explaining the true and correct history of this unique piece of technology will make even a liberal sit up, pay attention, and actually think!   YES, I AM IBM CERTIFIED! Any questions? This Carbine comes with an original IBM "OI B" marked 15 round magazine that was in the carbine when it was originally presented to me. I added (upgraded to) an additional single 30 round "high capacity" magazine that is marked only with "Made in U.S.A." (one that I had for years) to this display, simply because it was the proper thing to do to demonstrate my "proper respect" for the state of California's ban on high capacity magazines. It too will ship with this carbine. Note: Should you live in a liberal socialist state that doesn't like these particular magazines, give me a call and we CAN/WILL work something out!      A little statistical information on the I.B.M. M1 Carbine:   Main Manufacture and identification codes: "B"   Main plant location: Poughkeepsie, NY.   Average Cost to U.S. Government per completed rifle, $42.29   I.B.M. only made 350,000 +/- units during the production run of the M1 Carbine, or about 5.7% of all M1 Carbines made. An even smaller percentage of those carbines were made from the receivers produced for IBM by Auto Ordnance.    Below is the information on the internal components in this fine IBM M1 Carbine: IBM manufactured only 346,500 M1 Carbines in one assigned serial number block, accounting for approximately 5.7% of total M1 production during the war. IBM's assigned letter code was "B." This carbine has an IBM marked receiver bearing serial number (3880433) which places its date of manufacture in the January to March 1944 time period. It has an IBM marked 18” barrel with a shiny bore, post front sight, and the early Type 1 rear flip sight, and a fantastic (considering its age and history) an early high wood with "I" cut variety of walnut or birch stock that I believe is an arsenal replacement stock. The serial number is visible so you too can look up and verify the date of manufacture. The Barrel has the later IBM characteristic circumferential milling lines along the length except for the gas cylinder area and the front sight area. The barrel is marked "I.B.M. CORP." in clear visible stamped letters. There is no date on the barrel because IBM ceased dating their barrels after December 1943. There is a small "P" firing proof approximately halfway down the length of the barrel on top. The Barrel Band is a later Type 2 wide type, marked "AI" (for Inland or one of its subcontractors), and this carbine shows no sign of ever being "upgraded" to accommodate the wider Barrel Band with the bayonet lug. The post Front Sight is that is fabricated and is marked on the left side with an "IA". The rear flip sight is marked "S" on the right side.    The trigger housing is Type 2 single bevel marked "Q-NL",  which were made by Quality Hardware. The trigger markings are not visible or unmarked, and the hammer is marked "WA" for Winchester. This carbine still has the original unmarked "Push Button Safety". The slide is a Type III (Arm Joint 19/32") marked clearly with a "UN" and also has a very faint "O1(?)" stamp indicating that it is National Postal Meter (Underwood) located in the center of the piston well. The flat bolt is marked "AI" (Inland). It should also be noted that I was reminded by another extremely knowledgeable collector that there is often a difference between an all matching carbine and how it left the factory, as many M1 Carbine contractors shipped parts to other Contractors. Just because it has all matching doesn't necessary mean that is how it left the factory. So it's also possible that is exactly how it was when it left the factory! (An example, say Underwood was low on sears, Inland would ship some Sears to them. Sometimes marked or unmarked). There are known and documented shipments of bolts to I.B.M. (Inland shipped approximately 10,000 bolts to I.B.M. in late 1943), however there could be more shipments that occurred that are unknown. but this is a good reference. The dark matching high wood stock and two rivet upper hand guard are not marked by or for any contractor or subcontractor. While I do believe that it is not an factory original stock, and while I have been told many different things as to where this stock originated from, I believe this stock is an armory replacement of presentation quality done by Springfield Armory. I have been told that the "boxed S.A. over FLJ" cartouche makes this an "import", while others disagree, however I have yet to find anyone who has ever seen documentation or knows of this "importer", or even of anything close (again; I have been told a great many things over the years). This M1 Carbine stock also has the "Crossed Cannons Cartouche" on the right rear side of the stock just forward of the "I" cut sling well. There is also a "circle P" acceptance proof on the bottom base of the curved hand grip. The wood is dark and clean, however has a few very minor dings here and there from the many excursions to and from numerous data centers over the years. The hard wood is sound. with no soft spots or deep imperfections.To find a complete I.B.M. M1 Carbine .30 caliber with all "match-able" parts is amazingly rare, and assures its maximum "collector/safe queen" value. I have indeed had a few of those in my day and this carbine is neither. I will say that this is the finest looking carbine I have ever owned. I have never fired this weapon because "it just looks so nice on the wall". The past 10 years that I have been living in the Nevada desert, it has been stored "dry" (with no lubrications or grease) because of the dirt and dust in the dry desert air (it's nasty and gritty when it settles on oiled parts). Should the new owner decide to take this to the range to run a few rounds through it, I would first apply a liberal coat of gun oil and grease to the appropriate areas and parts. Check out the photos and see for yourself. This is truly one of those rare opportunities to own a “one of a kind” collectible. This is a fabulous M1 Carbine and it will be the envy of all you choose to let handle it.You can contact me via my personal email....newleetonytharpe@gmail.com
